Reference: Technical Architecture 2.3 (band config schema), 3 (full data
model), 5 (RBAC), and `/docs/specs/Data_Model_Identity_Addendum_v1.md`
(supersedes Architecture 3.1's entity list — identity model + previously
missing entities).

- Identity layer: `identities` (Supabase Auth link via `auth_user_id`;
  real email/phone; invite/`account_status` — passwords live in
  `auth.users`, never in Postgres) → `school_memberships` (identity ×
  school × member_type: teacher / admin / guardian / trainer_viewer) →
  actor profile tables. Web login is username (email or mobile) + password
  via Supabase Auth; phone OTP is recovery/2FA and WhatsApp-channel
  identity only — never web login. Authorization is always membership
  (tenant check first) + scoped role — admin gate is
  `member_type = 'admin'`, not a flat role on `teachers`. The child never
  has an identity row; guardians have no web invite/password path in this
  phase.
- Guardians link to children via `guardian_child_links` (join table, up to
  three per child, created by the WhatsApp handshake) — never an array
  column on `child`.
- Core config tables: `bands`, `subjects`, `band_subjects`, `outcomes`,
  `grade_scales`, plus `curriculum_areas` (11 Curriculum 2077 skill areas —
  system of record for tagging), `rollup_domains` + `area_domain_crosswalk`
  (the 6 parent-facing domains), `prompts` keyed `(feature_id, band_id)`,
  and the feature × band × school flag table. A band row carries
  `assessment_mode` and `aggregation_rule` as columns — read them, don't
  branch on grade number.
- `student_outcomes.attempt` is an ENUM('regular','after_support') — the
  two-pass record is one table with a flag, not two tables. The regular-pass
  value is immutable; a re-assessment inserts a new row, it never overwrites.
- `remedial_plans` is a first-class object with its own lifecycle (Opened →
  Activity delivered → Re-assessed → Escalated → Closed), not a status flag
  bolted onto `student_outcomes`. See Architecture 4.2 for the full state
  table and triggers.
- `teacher_sections(section_id, subject_id, is_class_teacher)` is the RBAC
  backbone. A teacher may hold multiple rows — an oversight row
  (`is_class_teacher = true`, subject-independent read) plus one or more
  subject rows (write-scoped). Pre-primary: one row, `subject_id = NULL`,
  `is_class_teacher` implicitly true.
- RLS enforcement, every table referencing `child_id`/`section_id`/
  `teacher_id`: write scope is `(section_id, subject_id)`; read scope is
  section-wide for any `is_class_teacher = true` row, and also section-wide
  (but write-locked to her subject) for a subject teacher.
- Substitute-teacher role: a `substitute_access` row (section, grantor,
  `expires_at`) — expiry is data, not application folklore. Rating/outcome
  confirmation is disabled at the RLS/application layer, not just hidden in
  UI. Anything she notices routes unconfirmed to the class teacher's queue.
- Consent and safety are rows, not conventions: `consents` (per
  guardian-child link, per consent type, grant/revoke timestamps — platform
  per-child access requires an audited session referencing a live consent)
  and `safeguarding_escalations` (append-only fast-path audit trail:
  routed-to, reviewed-by, resolution).
- `attendance_record` carries `recorded_by` (class teacher's duty; the
  substitute's only write). `child` carries `status`
  (active/promoted/transferred/exited), `dob`, and
  `report_language_override` — and, per the invariants, nothing about
  personality, traits, or risk.
- `handover_pack` is a materialized snapshot row, assembled at transition
  time — not a live join granted to the incoming teacher. It explicitly
  excludes coach-chat history (the join doesn't exist) and, from Grade 1,
  includes `portfolio_items` refs and open `remedial_plans` refs.
- When adding any new table that references a child or teacher: add both an
  RLS policy and a CI test asserting the policy covers both grains (tenant
  isolation + section/subject write scope), per Architecture 11.3.
